{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623537"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:12:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:12:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16868"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16868","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16868"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.06,0.1,0.08,0.72]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68666"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9558"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16868"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54123"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"9876"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22575"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22582"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68666","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68666"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system plays a crucial role in blood pressure regulation and fluid balance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary physiological effect of angiotensin II?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased cardiac contractility","Increased sodium excretion in the collecting ducts","Dilation of efferent arterioles","Inhibition of antidiuretic hormone release","Arteriolar vasoconstriction"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary physiological effect of angiotensin II is \u003Cstrong\u003Earteriolar vasoconstriction\u003C/strong\u003E. This powerful vasoconstrictor action leads to increased peripheral vascular resistance and elevated blood pressure. While angiotensin II has multiple effects, this direct vasoconstrictor action is its most immediate and significant impact on blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased sodium excretion in the collecting ducts\u003C/strong\u003E - Angiotensin II actually promotes sodium retention through stimulation of aldosterone release\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased cardiac contractility\u003C/strong\u003E - Angiotensin II increases cardiac contractility\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of antidiuretic hormone release\u003C/strong\u003E - Angiotensin II stimulates rather than inhibits antidiuretic hormone release\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDilation of efferent arterioles\u003C/strong\u003E - Angiotensin II causes constriction, not dilation, of efferent arterioles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important effects of angiotensin II include stimulation of aldosterone secretion, increased thirst, and enhanced sympathetic activity, but these are secondary to its primary vasoconstrictor action.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Angiotensin II increases blood pressure primarily by causing vasoconstriction of arterioles.","Angiotensin II stimulates aldosterone secretion from the adrenal cortex which increases sodium reabsorption.","The renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system helps maintain blood pressure and fluid volume homeostasis."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54123"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16868"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54123"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T09:13:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T09:17:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9558"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68666"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4926"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiov